<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Rhododendron</i> <i>columbianum</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Frangula</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Gaultheria</i> <i>shallon</i>, <i>Kalmia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Lonicera</i> <i>cauriana</i>, <i>Lonicera</i> <i>involucrata</i>, <i>Morella</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Rubus</i> <i>ursinus</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>orestera</i>, <i>Sambucus</i> <i>racemosa</i>, <i>Spiraea</i> <i>douglasii</i>, <i>Spiraea</i> <i>splendens</i> and <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>uliginosum</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Alnus</i> <i>rubra</i>, <i>Hesperocyparis</i> <i>pigmaea</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>muricata</i> or <i>Umbellularia</i> <i>californica</i>. Mosses may be present, including <i>Sphagnum</i> <i>subsecundum</i> and <i>Sphagnum</i> <i>teres</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open to continuous; mosses may be present. Tree layer is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer (cf. Christy 2004, NatureServe 2007, VegCAMP 2019, Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
		<li><i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer and <i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>murrayana</i> may be emergent in fen stands (Sikes et al. 2010a).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Moderate to gentle concave slopes and meadows at the bottom of broad valleys adjacent to streams, seeps, lakes, ponds, and saturated swales. Sites receive water from subsurface flows. Soils are high in organic matter and loamy. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> as an OBL plant in California. </div>
</div>

        
