<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Rhododendron columbianum </i>is an evergreen resinous shrub that grows to 1.5 m tall. The simple, leathery leaves with revolute margins cluster at the stem tips with fragrant, white flowers. Plants produce numerous, wind-dispersed seeds after their capsules split. Seeds require light to germinate from short-lived seed bank. Seedlings are small, grow slowly, and establish best in moist areas with discontinuous moss cover. Plants have shallow roots and rhizomes. Buds sprout from stems, root crowns, and rhizomes when plants are damaged (Gucker 2006b). Older manuals use the name <i>Ledum glandulosum </i>(Hickman 1993)<i>, </i>but morphological and molecular methods confirm the plant as a member of <i>Rhododendron </i>(Harmaja 1990, 1991, Kron and Judd 1990). This is a wetland shrub closely related to the circumboreal Labrador tea, <i>Rhododendron </i>(<i>Ledum</i>) <i>groenlandicum</i>, and it also has been considered taxonomically a hybrid <i>Ledum ×columbianum</i> (USDA-NRCS 2012).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Rhododendron columbianum </i>grows along the coast of the Pacific Northwest and in northern California mountains on acidic soils with or without mosses. Although the species is common, we know only a few shrubland stands in California scattered along the coast in coastal valleys, and other stands occur in fen/meadow complexes in the Sierra Nevada (Holland 1986, Cooper and Wolf 2006). Along the coast, they resemble associations described by Christy (2004) for Oregon in which <i>Carex obnupta, Gaultheria shallon, </i>and <i>Sphagnum </i>spp. are associates. Associations are often in early seral settings in Oregon and Washington, such as disturbed coastal swamps and heavily elk-browsed edges of moist lowland forests associated with fens and other wetlands (Christy 2004, NatureServe 2007). Coastal and montane stands are currently combined in this alliance, though future analysis of wetland data may warrant splitting them into different shrub alliances as has been done in the NVC within North Pacific acidic bog & fen and Rocky Mountain fen groups.<br/>
<br/>
Over most of the range in California, <i>R. columbianum </i>clusters in swampy areas under tree canopies that may represent many alliances, including both subspecies of <i>Pinus contorta, </i>as in the coastal zone (Holland 1986) and in the Sierra Nevada (Potter 2005). Coastal, wet temperate as well as montane, cold temperate stands that lack tree canopies are included in this shrub alliance. However, cover and physiognomy across stands are quite variable with some as scrub with few scattered trees and others as woodland communities with a well-developed understory of shrubs. Stands can sometimes have higher tree cover (>10%). More sampling and analysis is needed to clarify the distribution and relationships of these wetland stands with varying cover in the tree layer, especially to determine if a <i>Pinus contorta </i>Swamp Forest Alliance is warranted as compared to this shrubland alliance.  In many sites along the North Coast where Mendocino cypress occur, Rhododendron columbianum often has the highest cover in stands that fall under the <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea - Pinus contorta ssp. bolanderi / Rhododendron columbianum</i> association of the California Coastal Cypress Coodland Alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
