    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> includes the Central California Coast (261A), Northern California Coast (263A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Klamath Mountains (M261A), Mono (341D), Southern Cascade (M261D), Sierra Nevada (M261E), and Warner Mountains (M261Gf).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aj). <i>Rhododendron columbianum </i> stands occur in the Upper Scott Mountains in the Shasta-Trinity National Forest (Sikes et al. 2012).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf). <i>Rhododendron columbianum </i> stands occur in the Lassen Creek Fen complex in the Warner Mountains and near Mineral Spring near the Oregon - California border (Cooper and Wolf 2006, Sikes et al. 2010a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-e, Ag-k). Stands on the Point Reyes Peninsula, including Inverness Ridge, in Marin Co. (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021), are ecologically similar to those of <i>Carex obnupta</i> and <i>Rubus spectabilis - Morella californica</i> alliances. Stands also occur north to Humboldt and Del Norte Cos., including observations at Big Lagoon County Park, Patrick’s Point State Park, Lake Earl Wildlife Area, and Tolowa State Park. A vegetation survey of Crescent City Marsh Wildlife Area (Imper and Sawyer 1992) found <i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> growing with <i>Calamagrostis nutkaensis, Carex obnupta, Deschampsia cespitosa,</i> and <i>Menyanthes trifoliata,</i> and with emergent <i>Morella californica</i> and <i>Picea sitchensis.</i> Stands have been mapped along the coast in Mendocino Co. (VegCAMP 2019). Herbarium records also suggest that stands of this species historically occurred at Pitkin Marsh in Sonoma Co. (CCH 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ed-e, Eg-h, Ek-l, Et). Sampled stands occur in acidic fens with relatively poor mineral ion supplies on the Eldorado, Plumas, and Tahoe national forests; they include fens with a dense ericaceous shrub canopy and <i>Pinus contorta</i> stunted or contorted, or with a pine canopy and shrub subcanopy (Cooper and Wolf 2006, Sikes et al. 2010a). Stands also occur in Yosemite and Sequoia-Kings Canyon National Parks (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> In California, known stands are restricted to a few sites along the foggy North Coast and the montane Sierra Nevada. Stands are often small (e.g., < 0.5 hectares), and some are adjacent to and affected by human activity such as housing developments, change in water tables, or timber harvest. Encroachment by taller, woody plants adversely affects stand species composition, which includes rare plants such as <i>Lilium occidentale, </i>a CNPS list 1B.1 plant, on the North Coast. These stands require periodic disturbance.

This alliance is ranked rare in California due to a low area of occupancy, a low number of occurrences, narrow environmental specificity, as well as several pervasive threats with negative population impacts, notably droughts and habitat alteration due to climate change. </div>
</div>

    

    

